            "answer_text": "Q: As a musician what do you always carry with you? There are a couple of ways to interpret this question. The short literal answer is that I always try to have a couple of picks in my pocket, even if I\u2019m not on a musical expedition, because you never know if you might get a chance to play someone\u2019s guitar or mandolin or tenor banjo, and they take up literally no space. Specifically I try to have a yellow Jim Dunlop Tortex .73mm, for guitar or banjo, and a slightly stiffer JD Tortex green .88mm for mandolin. Come to think of it, I generally don\u2019t leave home without a mandolin. Let\u2019s hear it for small sturdy instruments. (I generally have a couple in a small change purse, and it\u2019s worth noting that a bright yellow pick turns practically black after a week or two in that environment. Because money is dirty. Wash your hamds.) But hey, let\u2019s go a little farther: what are the bare minimum gadgets to carry along with instruments if I\u2019m going out with the intention of playing? (Let\u2019s assume this is not a gig, we\u2019re not plugging in or amplifying in any way.) I have with me: -the aforementioned picks -a clip-on digital tuner. Twenty-dollar tuners don\u2019t last for me\u2014for some reason they die in a few weeks. YMMV. I got a forty-dollar Boss TU10 and have been using the same one for five years, changing the battery every six months or so. -a single or double instrument stand. (Rare is the jam location that has them built in on the wall and my thanks to those venues!) -guitar capo and banjo capo -spare strings -a handy string-changing kit including pliers, clippers, a small awl for getting the strings off the tuner pegs, perhaps a stringwinding crank. -iPad. Invaluable. Loaded with lyric cheat sheets (could be sheet music too), lists of songs and tunes, and available for on-the-spot recording if I hear a tune I want to learn later. Also a tuner app (backup since its much less convenient than the clip-on). ",
